# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: jsonapi-spec
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:jsonapi-spec/content-negotiation] In computing, **content negotiation** refers to mechanisms defined as a part of HTTP that make it possible to serve different versions of a document (or more generally, representations of a resource) at the same URI, so that user agents can specify which version fits their capabilities the best.
[src:jsonapi-spec/content-negotiation] One classical use of this mechanism is to serve an image in GIF or PNG format, so that a browser that cannot display PNG images (e.g.
[src:jsonapi-spec/content-negotiation] MS Internet Explorer 4) will be served the GIF version.
[src:jsonapi-spec/content-negotiation] A resource may be available in several different representations; for example, it might be available in different languages or different media types.
[src:jsonapi-spec/content-negotiation] One way of selecting the most appropriate choice is to give the user an index page and let them select the most appropriate choice; however it is often possible to automate the choice based on some selection criteria.
[src:jsonapi-spec/content-negotiation] HTTP provides for several different content negotiation mechanisms including: server-driven (or proactive), agent-driven (or reactive), transparent, and/or hybrid combinations thereof.
[src:jsonapi-spec/content-negotiation] Server-driven or proactive content negotiation is performed by algorithms on the server which choose among the possible variant representations.
[src:jsonapi-spec/content-negotiation] This is commonly performed based on user agent-provided acceptance criteria.
[src:jsonapi-spec/content-negotiation] To summarize how this works, when a user agent submits a request to a server, the user agent informs the server what media types or other aspects of content presentation it understands with ratings of how well it understands them.
[src:jsonapi-spec/content-negotiation] More precisely, the user agent provides HTTP headers that lists acceptable aspects of the resource and quality factors for them.
[src:jsonapi-spec/content-negotiation] The server is then able to supply the version of the resource that best fits the user agent's needs.
[src:jsonapi-spec/content-negotiation] Where the 'q' - quality - factor for German is higher than that for English.
[src:jsonapi-spec/content-negotiation] Multiple HTTP headers are often supplied together for content format or, specifically media type, language and a few other aspects of a resource.
[src:jsonapi-spec/content-negotiation] In addition to the commonly used `Accept` header for Media Type, the `Accept-Language` header for language negotiation, RFC 7231 also describes `Accept-Charset` & `Accept-Encodings` for character encodings and content codings (compression) respectively.
[src:jsonapi-spec/content-negotiation] Neither RFC 7231 nor the more recent related specifications such as *Content Negotiation by Profile* specify how to resolve trade-offs in cases where different headers specify conflicting requirements, such as, in the above example, choosing between an HTML page in English and a GIF image in German.
[src:jsonapi-spec/content-negotiation] Agent-driven or reactive content negotiation is performed by algorithms in the user-agent which choose among the possible variant representations.
[src:jsonapi-spec/content-negotiation] This is commonly performed based on a server provided list of representations and metadata about them.
[src:jsonapi-spec/content-negotiation] To summarize how this works, when a user agent submits a request to a server, the server informs the user-agent which representations it has available as well as any metadata it has about each representation (e.g., content-type, quality, language, etc.).
[src:jsonapi-spec/content-negotiation] The user-agent then resubmits the request to a specific URL for the chosen representation.
[src:jsonapi-spec/content-negotiation] This can be automatically chosen by the user-agent or the user-agent can present the user with the choices and the user can directly choose such.
[src:jsonapi-spec/content-negotiation] More precisely, the server responds with either 300 Multiple Choices or 406 Not Acceptable (when server-driven, user-agent acceptance criteria are provided but the server cannot automatically make a selection).
[src:jsonapi-spec/content-negotiation] Unfortunately HTTP leaves the format of the list of representations and metadata along with selection mechanisms unspecified.
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] With HATEOAS, a client interacts with a network application whose application servers provide information dynamically through hypermedia.
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] A REST client needs little to no prior knowledge about how to interact with an application or server beyond a generic understanding of hypermedia.
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] By contrast, clients and servers in Common Object Request Broker Architecture (CORBA) interact through a fixed interface shared through documentation or an interface description language (IDL).
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] The restrictions imposed by HATEOAS decouple client and server.
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] This enables server functionality to evolve independently.
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] The term was coined in 2000 by Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] A user-agent makes an HTTP request to a REST API through an entry point URL.
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] All subsequent requests the user-agent may make are discovered inside the response to each request.
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] The media types used for these representations, and the link relations they may contain, are part of the API.
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] The client transitions through application states by selecting from the links within a representation or by manipulating the representation in other ways afforded by its media type.
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] In this way, RESTful interaction is driven by hypermedia, rather than out-of-band information.
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] The response contains these possible follow-up links: POST a deposit, withdrawal, transfer, or close request (to close the account).
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] As an example, later, after the account has been overdrawn, there is a different set of available links, because the account is overdrawn.
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] Now only one link is available: to deposit more money (by POSTing to deposits).
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] In its current *state*, the other links are not available.
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] Hence the term *Engine of Application State*.
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] What actions are possible varies as the state of the resource varies.
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] A client does not need to understand every media type and communication mechanism offered by the server.
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] The ability to understand new media types may be acquired at run-time through "code-on-demand" provided to the client by the server.
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] The HATEOAS constraint is an essential part of the "uniform interface" feature of REST, as defined in Roy Fielding's doctoral dissertation.
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] Fielding has further described the concept on his blog.
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] The purpose of some of the strictness of this and other REST constraints, Fielding explains, is "software design on the scale of decades: every detail is intended to promote software longevity and independent evolution.
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] Many of the constraints are directly opposed to short-term efficiency.
[src:jsonapi-spec/hateoas] Unfortunately, people are fairly good at short-term design, and usually awful at long-term design".
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:jsonapi-spec/json] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] In information and communications technology, a **media type**, **content type** or **MIME type** is a two-part identifier for file formats and content formats.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] Their purpose is comparable to filename extensions and uniform type identifiers, in that they identify the intended data format.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] They are mainly used by technologies underpinning the Internet, and also used on Linux desktop systems.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] The Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) is the official authority for the standardization and publication of these classifications.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] Media types are also used by other internet protocols such as HTTP, document file formats such as HTML, and the XDG specifications implemented by Linux desktop environments, for similar purposes.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] Different internet standards or web standards bodies differ on the preferred term for this type of identifier.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] The IANA and IETF use the term "media type", and consider the term "MIME type" to be obsolete, since media types have become used in contexts unrelated to email, such as HTTP.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] By contrast, the WHATWG continues to use the term "MIME type" and discourages use of the term "media type" as ambiguous, since it is used with a different meaning in connection with the CSS `@media` feature.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] The HTTP response header for providing the media type is `Content-Type`.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] The W3C has used `ContentType` as an XML data-type name for a media type.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] XDG specifications implemented by Linux desktop environments continue to use the term "MIME type".
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] A media type consists of a *type* and a *subtype*, which is further structured into a *tree*.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] As an example, an HTML file might be designated `text/html; charset=UTF-8`.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] In this example, `text` is the type, `html` is the subtype, and `charset=UTF-8` is an optional parameter indicating the character encoding.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] Types, subtypes, and parameter names are case-insensitive.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] Parameter values are usually case-sensitive, but may be interpreted in a case-insensitive fashion depending on the intended use.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] The "type" part defines the broad use of the media type.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] As of November 1996, the registered types were `application`, `audio`,`image`, `message`, `multipart`, `text` and `video`.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] By July 2024, the registered types included the foregoing, plus `font`, `example`, `model`, and `haptics`.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] An unofficial top-level type in common use is `chemical`, used for chemical file formats.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] A subtype typically consists of a media format, but it may or must also contain other content, such as a tree prefix, producer, product or suffix, according to the different rules in registration trees.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] All media types should be registered using the IANA registration procedures.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] For the efficiency and flexibility of the media type registration process, different structures of subtypes can be registered in registration trees that are distinguished by the use of tree prefixes.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] Currently, the following trees are created: standard (no prefix), vendor (`vnd.` prefix), personal or vanity (`prs.` prefix), unregistered (`x.` prefix).
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] These registration trees were first defined in November 1996 (obsoleted RFC 2048 - currently RFC 6838).
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] New registration trees may be created by IETF Standards Action for external registration and management by well-known permanent organizations (e.g. scientific societies).
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] The standards tree does not use any tree prefix.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] Examples are `text/javascript`, `image/png`.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] Registrations in the standards tree must be either associated with IETF specifications approved directly by the IESG, or registered by an IANA recognized standards-related organization.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] The vendor tree includes media types associated with publicly available products.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] Examples are: `application/vnd.ms-excel`, `application/vnd.oasis.opendocument.text`.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] The terms "vendor" and "producer" are considered equivalent in the context.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] Industry consortia as well as non-commercial entities can register media types in the vendor tree.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] A registration in the vendor tree may be created by anyone who needs to interchange files associated with some software product or set of products.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] However, the registration belongs to the vendor or organization producing the software that employs the type being registered, and that vendor or organization can at any time elect to assert ownership of a registration done by a third party.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] The personal or vanity tree includes media types associated with non publicly available products or experimental media types.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] Examples are `audio/prs.sid`, `image/prs.btif`.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] The unregistered tree includes media types intended exclusively for use in private environments and only with the active agreement of the parties exchanging them.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] Examples are `application/x.foo`, `video/x.bar`.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] Media types in this tree cannot be registered.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] This type was originally defined in RFC 1590 (published in September 1993) using the `x-` or `X-` prefix.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] RFC 2048 (published in November 1996) introduced the `x.` prefix, but discouraged use of the unregistered tree, as new personal and vendor trees with relaxed registration requirements are now available.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] The current RFC 6838 (published in January 2013) maintains the same recommendation, but subtypes prefixed with `x-` or `X-` are no longer considered to be members of this tree.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] Media types that have been widely deployed (with a subtype prefixed with `x-` or `X-`) without being registered, should be, if possible, re-registered with a proper prefixed subtype.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] If this is not possible, the media type can, after an approval by both the media types reviewer and the IESG, be registered in the standards tree with its unprefixed subtype.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] `application/x-www-form-urlencoded` is an example of a widely deployed type that ended up registered with the `x-` prefix.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] Suffix is an augmentation to the media type definition to additionally specify the underlying structure of that media type, allowing for generic processing based on that structure and independent of the exact type's particular semantics.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] Media types that make use of a named structured syntax should use the appropriate IANA registered `"+"suffix` for that structured syntax when they are registered.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] Unregistered suffixes should not be used (since January 2013).
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] Structured syntax suffix registration procedures are defined in RFC 6838.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] The +xml suffix has been defined since January 2001 (RFC 3023), and was formally included in the initial contents of the Structured Syntax Suffix Registry along with `+json`, `+ber`, `+der`, `+fastinfoset`, `+wbxml`, and `+zip` in January 2013 (RFC 6839).
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] Subsequent additions include `+gzip`, `+cbor`, `+json-seq`, and `+cbor-seq`.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] Mailcap (derived from the phrase "mail capability") is a type of meta file used to configure how MIME-aware applications such as mail clients and web browsers render files of different MIME-types.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] The mailcap format is defined by RFC 1524 "A User Agent Configuration Mechanism for Multimedia Mail Format Information" but is not defined as an Internet standard.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] Lines can be comments starting with the # character, or a mime-type followed by how to handle that mime type.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] An associated file is the **mime.types** file, which associates filename extensions with a *MIME type*.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] If the MIME type is properly set, this is unnecessary, but MIME types may be incorrectly set, or set to a generic type such as `application/octet-stream`, and **mime.types** allows one to fall back on the extension in these cases.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] Similarly, since many file systems do not store MIME type information, but instead rely on the filename extension, a mime.types file is frequently used by web servers to determine MIME type.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] When *viewing* a file, these two work together as follows: **`mime.types`** associates an extension with a MIME type, while `mailcap` associates a MIME type with a program.
[src:jsonapi-spec/media-type] In UNIX-type systems, the mime.types file is usually located at `/etc/**mime.types**` and/or `$HOME/**.mime.types**` and the format is simply that each line is a space-delimited list of a MIME type, followed by zero or more extensions.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:jsonapi-spec/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] A **web API** is an application programming interface (API) for either a web server or a web browser.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] As a web development concept, it can be related to a web application's client side (including any web frameworks being used).
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed **endpoints** to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] A server API (SAPI) is not considered a server-side web API, unless it is publicly accessible by a remote web application.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] A client-side web API is a programmatic interface to extend functionality within a web browser or other HTTP client.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] Originally these were most commonly in the form of native plug-in browser extensions however most newer ones target standardized JavaScript bindings.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] The Mozilla Foundation created their WebAPI specification which is designed to help replace native mobile applications with HTML5 applications.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] Google created their Native Client architecture which is designed to help replace insecure native plug-ins with secure native sandboxed extensions and applications.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] They have also made this portable by employing a modified LLVM AOT compiler.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed *endpoints* to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] The web API is exposed most commonly by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] Endpoints are important aspects of interacting with server-side web APIs, as they specify where resources can be accessed by third-party software.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] Usually the access is via a URI to which HTTP requests are posted, and from which the response is thus expected.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] Web APIs may be public or private, the latter of which requires an *access token*.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] Endpoints need to be static, otherwise the correct functioning of software that interacts with them cannot be guaranteed.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] If the location of a resource changes (and with it the endpoint) then previously written software will break, as the required resource can no longer be found at the same place.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] As API providers still want to update their web APIs, many have introduced a versioning system in the URI that points to an endpoint.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] Web 2.0 Web APIs often use machine-based interactions such as REST and SOAP.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] RESTful web APIs use HTTP methods to access resources via URL-encoded parameters, and use JSON or XML to transmit data.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] By contrast, SOAP protocols are standardized by the W3C and mandate the use of XML as the payload format, typically over HTTP.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] Furthermore, SOAP-based Web APIs use XML validation to ensure structural message integrity, by leveraging the XML schemas provisioned with WSDL documents.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] A WSDL document accurately defines the XML messages and transport bindings of a Web service.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] Server-side web APIs are interfaces for the outside world to interact with the business logic.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] For many companies this internal business logic and the intellectual property associated with it are what distinguishes them from other companies, and potentially what gives them a competitive edge.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] They do not want this information to be exposed.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] However, in order to provide a web API of high quality, there *needs* to be a sufficient level of documentation.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] One API provider that not only provides documentation, but also links to it in its error messages is Twilio.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] However, there are now directories of popular documented server-side web APIs.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] The number of available web APIs has grown consistently over the past years, as businesses realize the growth opportunities associated with running an open platform, that any developer can interact with.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] ProgrammableWeb tracks over 24000 Web APIs that were available in 2022, up from 105 in 2005.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] There are few major software applications/services that do not offer some form of web API.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] One of the most common forms of interacting with these web APIs is via embedding external resources, such as tweets, Facebook comments, YouTube videos, etc.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] In fact there are very successful companies, such as Disqus, whose main service is to provide embeddable tools, such as a feature-rich comment system.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] Any website of the TOP 100 Alexa Internet ranked websites uses APIs and/or provides its own APIs, which is a very distinct indicator for the prodigious scale and impact of web APIs as a whole.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] As the number of available web APIs has grown, open source tools have been developed to provide more sophisticated search and discovery.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] APIs.json provides a machine-readable description of an API and its operations, and the related project APIs.io offers a searchable public listing of APIs based on the APIs.json metadata format.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] Many companies and organizations rely heavily on their Web API infrastructure to serve their core business clients.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] In 2014 Netflix received around 5 billion API requests, most of them within their private API.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] Many governments collect a lot of data, and some governments are now opening up access to this data.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] The interfaces through which this data is typically made accessible are web APIs.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] Web APIs allow for data, such as "budget, public works, crime, legal, and other agency data" to be accessed by any developer in a convenient manner.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] An example of a popular web API is the Astronomy Picture of the Day API operated by the American space agency NASA.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] It is a server-side API used to retrieve photographs of space or other images of interest to astronomers, and metadata about the images.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] The documentation states that this endpoint accepts GET requests.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] It requires one piece of information from the user, an API key, and accepts several other optional pieces of information.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] Such pieces of information are known as *parameters*.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] The parameters for this API are written in a format known as a query string, which is separated by a question mark character (`?`) from the endpoint.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] An ampersand (`&`) separates the parameters in the query string from each other.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] Together, the endpoint and the query string form a URL that determines how the API will respond.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] This URL is also known as a *query* or an *API call*.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] In the below example, two parameters are transmitted (or *passed*) to the API via the query string.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] The first is the required API key and the second is an optional parameter — the date of the photograph requested.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] Visiting the above URL in a web browser will initiate a GET request, calling the API and showing the user a result, known as a *return value* or as a *return*.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] This API returns JSON, a type of data format intended to be understood by computers, but which is somewhat easy for a human to read as well.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] The above API return has been reformatted so that names of JSON data items, known as *keys*, appear at the start of each line.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] Although this API can be called by an end user with a web browser (as in this example) it is intended to be called automatically by software or by computer programmers while writing software.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] JSON is intended to be parsed by a computer program, which would extract the URL of the photograph and the other metadata.
[src:jsonapi-spec/web-api] The resulting photo could be embedded in a website, automatically sent via text message, or used for any other purpose envisioned by a software developer.
